# **Executive Summary**  {#executive-summary}

**Objective:** To research and analyze Goodwill’s Performance Management Plan. (PMP) To understand how PMP affects employees on various levels and the employees' points of view. To grasp how Goodwill's PMP functions and compile the strengths and areas of improvement of the overall PMP process instituted. To applaud the strengths noticed, and to make recommendations on how to develop areas of improvement identified. To research what is working in the market today, and ensure our recommendations align with what is proven to be successful. To develop SMART goals based on those recommendations, as well as a business case to support them. To address any challenges we may need to overcome with implementing the SMART goals. 

**Methodologies:** We used a variety of methodologies, including researching the organization directly through various online resources. We also developed a survey based on a class rubric to gather information directly from employees. We hosted 3 separate interviews with different types of employees focused on the survey, a Retail Sales Associate, a Human Resources(HR) admin, and an HR Manager. We then took the answers from each employee and compiled them to look for overall trends, consistencies, and inconsistencies. We identified areas of improvement and researched the best ways to improve those areas. We compiled those suggestions and research and created SMART goals based on the data.

**Findings:** We found that while Goodwill does have a Performance Management Plan in place and there are some good intentions with the PMP, there are a lot of areas of opportunity to improve. They utilize a fair structured PMP grading process across multiple behavioral areas \- though they lack transparency with all employees on those definitions. Goodwill does provide a development questionnaire \- though it’s only provided to targeted employees. We also discovered that employees are not elicited for input on development/performance goals that directly affect them, and there’s a lack of 360 and continuous consistent frequent feedback. Employees aren’t awarded via a merit system and instead are offered the same monetary award as others regardless of performance. Additionally, training on the PMP wasn’t consistent across employees, HR admin, and management to the point that each employee provided a different answer on vision, mission, and objective as well as what the actual PMP entails.

**Recommendations:**  We recommend implementing PMP training for all levels of employees ensuring transparency in the process top-down. We recommend incorporating employee involvement in the development goal process as well as frequent formal 360 feedback. Additionally, initiating a merit-based reward system for employees and calibrating management will be crucial to Goodwill's turnaround.

# **Assessment of PMP in the Organization** {#assessment-of-pmp-in-the-organization}

## **Performance Management Overview**  {#performance-management-overview}

Performance management is a set of tools, techniques, and a system of processes that allows your managers and leaders to not just monitor employee performance and project progress, but also support the employees’ goals they set for themselves[^1]. Performance management is beneficial to the following: enables ongoing performance management, provides 360-degree performance reviews, improves frequency and quality of feedback, makes it easier to track employee’s performance and progress, helps identify training needs and opportunities, and finally automates and streamline performance review reports. According to statistics, 80% of the youthful generation wants instant feedback rather than wait for the end of the year[^2]. This is because it leaves a 12 month gap of forgetting your goals you set in that time. It is important to write things down\!  In addition, only 5% of HR management find the performance review process to be satisfactory. Finally, 51% of employees believe that annual reviews are inaccurate because a singular review cannot capture all angles of performance, accurately. The performance management process encapsulates key human resources like employee training for improved performance, acknowledgement of good work, goal-setting, and continuous progress review.   
We explained the definition, but what makes a good PMP system? An effective PMP system is one that is continuous and not annual. This creates more transparency for both management and the subordinates. Verbal performance exchanges and reviews are meaningful and not just a routine task. This can boost team morale and make the employees feel like they make an impact. Finally, utilizing a user-friendly performance management software, like Paycom, that grants management performance activity in real time. You have to use the tools effectively to have an impact on your team. Using the PMP correctly can boost team morale and it can provide transparency for both management and the employees.

An effective PMP system serves many purposes for a company. It can improve the company’s profit margin because it reduces employee turnover, which helps generate great business results. It gives employees a clear vision for a career path by ensuring that supervisors are providing meaningful feedback and are setting their subordinates for success. Feedback can be more engaging and proactive, furnishing staff with valuable progressive feedback. In addition, it ensures subordinates attain their SMART goals and they know what is expected of them. Goals that are regularly set and often discussed are often more effective than only speaking about them once a year. In conclusion, having an effective PMP is important depending how you use it. It boosts morale and it keeps employees motivated, generating more productivity in the workplace.

The types of PMP systems include the following: general appraisal, 360 degree feedback, employee self assessment, manager performance appraisal, and project evaluation review. The PMP system is flexible and there are many ways to provide feedback to both an employee and a manager. The PMP stages include planning a development plan, acting on the objectives, tracking progress, and reviewing accomplishments and pinpoint lessons learned. How are we going to implement a robust system to an entire organization? First, we have to clarify the expectations so employees understand the output and attitudes. Second, we observe and assist performance and intervene where and when necessary to ensure compliance. Third, we evaluate performances by assessing the outcomes in the process of task execution. Finally, we interact and positively review by discussing performance, shared observations, requests for employee feedback, and working with subordinates to work on self improvement.

Finally, I will discuss the advantages and disadvantages of having a PMP system. Let’s start with the advantages: it improves consistency in workers’ performance. This is because it is designed to carefully select a set of parameters suited for the company’s objectives. It recognizes great talent and opens the door for more effective training programs, leading to professional growth. It motivates employees and it boosts company morale because it can be used as an avenue to celebrate personal wins. This one is important, it saves time. Instead of waiting for the end of the year, employees can make corrective actions mid year, saving valuable time for both employees and management. Lastly, the newer PMP systems automate the performance reviews due to the advancement of HR related softwares. As mentioned, it provides feedback and transparency in real time. Unfortunately with any system, there will also be disadvantages. Some of the disadvantages include inconsistency, prejudice, time consuming, and discouragement. Busy schedules can make management lose focus, and only remember the negative aspects of an employee. It can be human nature to be biased during the process, so the way to eliminate this is by creating a structured process. PMP systems can be time consuming and a tedious drafting process depending how many employees work at a company. It can cause discouragement amongst employees if only negative feedback is provided and it is not reinforced by positive feedback. In summary, PMP has its strengths and weaknesses, but if used effectively, it can outweigh the cost. Most businesses rely on PMP to encourage employees to stay motivated, ultimately increasing productivity in the workplace[^3].

## **Performance Management Process for Goodwill**  {#performance-management-process-for-goodwill}

The Performance Management process at Goodwill varies depending on the role. For example, it will look different for a retail store associate compared to an administrative employee. Here, we will discuss the overall process from the viewpoint of a retail sales associate, HR employee, and HR manager and compare the similarities and differences in the performance management process.  
	  
When employees are onboarded, they are introduced to basic training in the performance management process. This is more of an introduction to the basics based partially on common sense and is reviewed more in-depth in the employees’ first 6-month review when there are actual observations and feedback on the employee's work. Depending on the position, the employee will get varying levels of details on the performance management process \- for example, baseline employees aren’t given definitions for what defines good quality of work in the same written manner that admin employees are. Formal reviews are given after 6 months for new hires, and then annually thereafter. It should be noted that even though annual reviews are scheduled, they are often delivered to the employees later than anticipated. If managers are late frequently enough, corrective and preventive action (CAPA) may take place \- though this is flexible and not set in stone. As feedback is typically done annually, depending on the type of infraction \- the employee may get more immediate feedback, done at the discretion of the manager. Additionally, if an employee isn’t performing well, as determined by the manager \- they can increase the frequency of the feedback sessions to once every 30 days to try and find a way to help the employee be successful. While this is a formal process, it’s also flexible from the standpoint that the goal is to get the employee from being an underperformer to being a performer. There may be occasional informal conversations, but nothing consistent in the form of continual/360 feedback or even more consistent formal follow-ups with direct managers. This implies if you’re not having more frequent meetings that you are contributing sufficiently. When feedback is required, emails are sent to the employee's manager well in advance, and then the feedback or performance management will be completed in a private room with the manager and employee. A (CAPA) may be assigned depending on any infractions by the employee.

Standards of performance are going to vary, but there didn’t seem to be a consistent guideline to what it meant to be a solid performer for baseline employees. There are limitations to things you can’t do, but more of a common sense guideline is used. Employees do get rated based on performance in their reviews, and then managers give the employees feedback and goals based on their performance. Managers will give a rating of 1-5 on various categories including using resources available effectively, organizing and prioritizing work, quality of work, productivity, etc. Each section is individually rated from 1-5 and then is weighted 6.25% out of the total sections which is then totaled together for an overall score. A lower score in any section implies this area needs room for improvement, and with a 5 being, you’re doing a great job in that category. This is a fair and upfront approach where employees can focus on individual development areas \- however, it’s lacking in terms of a clear definition of what is meant by “Quality of Work” which may be confusing to employees and requires them to ask clarifying questions. Admin employees on the other hand have a more clear and defined idea of what Quality of Work actually means, as well as clearly defined definitions for each category they are graded on. These same definitions are not communicated in the same way to baseline employees though. Additionally, results are not calibrated. Meaning, that an employee's manager compiles and delivers those results solely without needing input from other managers/employees. This is important because it shows a lack of consistency across standards of performance. Knowing that different managers will grade differently based on different things, if there’s no calibration or agreement then there will be inconsistent standards across the managers, as well as the employees. Due to admin having slightly fewer categories, their weighted average per question is a little higher at 7.69%. While the PMP is more robust for admin employees, it is lacking in terms of transparency to baseline employees.

Goals are established by an individual's manager, or potentially a higher level depending on the goal, typically without employee input into the goals construction. Proactive employees can provide input on goals, though these are still established by the manager. Goals are also graded at the discretion of the manager, though employees are allowed to provide feedback. Managers prepare their employees' performance ratings, goals, and any relevant feedback annually, and then provide employees the opportunity to provide feedback in return on their annual review.  This would be an optimal time to provide input on goals as well. Goal setting coming from management and above arguably does align with the overall organizational strategy and goals \- as they are responsible for implementing the organizational strategy and goals. That said, not involving the employee in this process may be contributing to the lack of consistently knowing the organization's strategy and goals across all 3 employees interviewed. An example goal was increasing the number of racks processed per shift for a retail associate, or being more aware of safety. (pictured) These goals align closely with individual job roles and will vary depending on the position. From a standard employee point of view, that is the extent of their contributions to their goals aside from completing the ones assigned to them. Admin employees and above exclusively are given the option of an additional Professional Development Questionnaire that includes development questions including “What areas do you feel you need to improve on?” and “If you could change one thing about your job today, what would it be?” The questionnaire consists of 15 questions focused on different types of development type questions and is one-sided from the employee, meaning the employee fills it out and discusses it with their manager but doesn’t necessarily get written feedback. This form is also solely available to admin and above, meaning base employees are not eligible or even aware of the form. 

Accomplishing or exceeding expectations on your goals does not mean you will receive a larger raise than others who do not. Each position has a pay-coded structure and you a % raise the same as everyone else based on performance. This speaks to the lack of a merit system \- which demonstrates that a poor-performing and a high-performing employee who are both in the same position, will also receive the same monetary compensation in the form of a raise at the end of the year. Unfortunately, this may lead high-performing employees to disengage knowing they will not make more money unless they get promoted. The only way for an employee to get a larger raise is by promotion. Based on an employee's consistent performance, they may be eligible for various promotions throughout the organization. Acknowledging this \- Goodwill provides complementary training and certifications available to employees who wish to grow. They have a partnership with multiple local learning programs where employees can take extra classes towards various certifications to help advance their careers, at either no cost or a significantly reduced cost depending on the class/certification. Even though this is available to employees, it’s not necessarily advertised or promoted to employees consistently \- employees would need to be more proactive and reach out to their manager to take advantage of this program. 

## **Activities, Investments, and Strengths**  {#activities,-investments,-and-strengths}

While Goodwill does have a Performance Management Plan in place, it doesn’t necessarily have the most solid practice in place. That said, there are some things they are doing well. For example, they have a flexible, fair, and more recently transparent performance management plan in place, they institute a tuition reimbursement type program and they have begun rolling out basic self-development plans. 

| Strengths | Opportunities for Improvement  |
| :---- | :---- |
| Performance Management Plan is flexible and fair | Can increase transparency and training of programs to incorporate all employees more |
| Tuition reimbursement type program for employee development | Can incorporate employee input when designing development and performance goals |
| Began rolling out development style questionnaires to targeted employees | Can establish a merit based system that recognizes individual employee achievements |

Goodwill also has a performance management plan that can pivot as needed due to its flexibility. An example of this is increasing the frequency of meetings with employees that are underperforming. There could be numerous reasons why someone is underperforming, and having flexibility and the genuine approach of wanting to help the employee perform as needed helps foster a positive focus on this issue. For example, Evalflow mentions that managers that are flexible and adapt their approach to fit the needs and strengths of their employees can incur many benefits including improved engagement and retention, increased productivity and performance, and allows them to encourage growth and development. Rather than being rigid and holding everyone to the same standard, flexibility is key to unlocking each employee's strengths. Some employees are going to be stronger at different tasks than others, and recognizing this while putting your employees in an environment where they will succeed is crucial. Instead, listening to your employees and helping them as you can is far more beneficial than forcing someone to be 100% compliant with something they may struggle with.

They utilize a fair grading system of evenly distributed categories they want to focus on, and for admin employees, they provide clear definitions of what each category means. It could be beneficial to put examples of different behaviors that would fall under the categories \- though right now it’s left to be a bit more subjective. Goodwill has recently begun using Paycom which offers a bit more transparency into the performance management process which is vital to boosting employee engagement and retention. Florentina Greger states “Performance management systems that encourage transparency, fairness, and growth opportunities contribute to a workplace where everyone feels respected and empowered. Employees who are engaged and satisfied with their work environment are likely to remain loyal to the organization.” This goes on to demonstrate the value of being transparent with your performance management process. It’s more cost-effective to keep an employee than to pay to replace them.

Goodwill has a tuition reimbursement-type program to help with self-development within their performance management plan by encouraging employee development through free and/or heavily subsidized learning programs for various classes, skills, or certificates. This is a huge finding in the performance management plan because tuition reimbursement programs have so many benefits from productivity and also a cost savings standpoint. Even though the organization is paying for the education in some form in the backend, the benefits will outweigh the costs. Shayna Joubert writes in the Northeastern University Graduate Program blog, that some of the benefits attained by tuition reimbursement programs include attracting talent, reducing turnover, boosting employee development and engagement, as well as saving money. Referenced in the same article \- an Accenture study found that for every $1 spent on educational assistance, they saved an average of $1.29 on recruiting costs. This shows that investing in your employees is overall more beneficial than not, by reducing turnover alone there are huge cost savings. Mix in the additional benefits of getting better talent, and increased employee development and engagement \- and that exemplifies the amount already saved. From a performance management viewpoint, having employees who are more engaged and developed is more beneficial to the organization when it comes to deliverables and end products. In other words, having a happy, engaged, developed employee on the retail floor greeting your customers is a lot better than the alternative disengaged, undeveloped employee.

From our interviews with Goodwill, they have begun rolling out a development plan document to admin and above which provides opportunities for employee feedback and self-development type questions. While this isn’t a robust development system as of yet and is only available to select employees, it does lay the groundwork for developing one in the near future which is important because self-development plans are proven to be beneficial to both the employee as well as the organization they work for. According to PeopleGoal, the development planning process plays a crucial role for both staff and the organizations they work for through 6 main key benefits which are, upskilling the workforce, increasing productivity, improving employee satisfaction and increasing retention, enriching company culture as well as strengthening feedback culture. The fact that Goodwill has already begun implementing one shows they recognize the value in self-development, this is a work in progress though that should only lead to more company benefits the more this process is invested in. 

## **Areas for Improvement**  {#areas-for-improvement}

Weaknesses and inefficiencies exist in all aspects of a business and can have a significant impact on a company’s performance management process. As such, it is critical to identify all areas for improvement to rectify them, and if not, at least acknowledge them. While Goodwill Industries is a nonprofit organization known for its used goods stores, donation-resale model, and community-based programs, not much is known about its operational processes. Through our interviews, we identified no explicitly stated company vision, strategic direction, or core values; these are only implied and subject to self-interpretation. As noted by Peak Frameworks, “A vision statement articulates an organization's long-term goals and aspirations, essentially serving as its ‘north star’.”[^4] The strategic direction focuses on the creation of a forward-focused vision, the removal of biases and flaws in reasoning, and the tracking of progress based on strategic goals.[^5] Lastly, as per an article from Lesley University, “Holding employees to a company standard can help shape the way they do their jobs. When company values are defined and enforced, it can inspire workers to hold themselves to a higher standard. It also makes employee criticism a matter of living up to those values, rather than a personal attack.”[^6] Overall, it can be seen that having an explicitly stated company vision, strategic direction, and core values is non-negotiable for organizations. With them in place, it is possible to align them with the performance management process and ensure the company is moving in a unified direction.

Another area for improvement is that both development and performance goals should be included in the performance management process. Currently, only the development goal exists, however, it is being used more for what a performance goal is than a developmental one. As noted by Lorelei, “Combining performance and development goals in evaluations provides a balanced view of both immediate job effectiveness and long-term career growth. This integration means employees are meeting current expectations and advancing their skills.”[^7] An additional issue with the current goal-setting practices is that only administrative employees are allowed to set their own goals. Non-administrative employees have their goals set by their direct manager or upper management. This is problematic because goal setting encourages independent thinking while fostering a sense of self-reliance both professionally and personally, leading to an increase in accountability and the probability of success.[^8]

An additional area for improvement is providing more consistent personalized formal and informal feedback throughout the performance management process. As it stands, the only form of constant feedback is the general group feedback, done every month that reviews performance metrics. For personalized feedback, there is only the formal performance management review done biannually for new hires and annually for more tenured employees. To quote Christopher, “Periodic feedback sessions give the manager and employee multiple opportunities to calibrate and recalibrate their joint efforts. Like two paths diverging, the longer it takes between the time the manager and employee speak about a performance problem, the greater the distance will be between planned and actual performance improvement.”[^9] This is why continuous feedback is critical, as it not only increases productivity but also fosters successful partnerships.

Another area for improvement is to provide on-time performance management feedback. From our interviews, we found that while the performance management process is always followed for each employee, the formal feedback timing is heavily dependent on their direct manager. With timely feedback, employees can make quick improvements by correcting their behavior or performance sooner. It can also reduce anxiety, as no one enjoys the constant ambiguity, even when they are confident in their performance. Lastly, because there is an optimal time for feedback, when delayed for too long, problems will only pile up while enthusiasm will diminish.[^10] As the saying goes, “The best time to plant a tree was twenty years ago, and the second best time is today.”

An additional area for improvement is tying the performance management process to a merit reward system. As it stands, at the end of every year, every employee of the same title is given the same increase regardless of their prior year’s performance management results. Those achieving excellent results are given a pat on the back, while those underachieving are told to do better without any meaningful consequences. To obtain a merit raise, the sole option is through a promotion. While the performance management process can be said to be somewhat tied to the promotion process, how often and how frequently can promotions realistically occur? As noted in an article from Darwinbox, “The benefits of implementing such a system are numerous. It increases employee motivation by linking rewards to performance. Employees are encouraged to maximize their abilities. And, productivity improves when employees are recognized for their hard work, inspiring others to do the same.”[^11] Overall, the distinction between excellent and poor performers needs to be made both to reward achievers and inspire underperformers.

Another area for improvement is to require training for both managers and employees regarding the performance management process in terms of expected performance standards, calibration standards, and the importance of goal setting. Presently, neither managers nor employees are required to have any level of substantial training on the performance management process and take it at face value. Managers view the process more as a legal requirement set by CARF (Commission on Accreditation of Rehabilitation Facilities) than a means of increasing employee engagement, decreasing attrition rates, and reducing the cost of hiring. To further support these claims, companies with greater-than-average levels of employee engagement reported 27% higher earnings and 38% higher productivity. Additionally, a study conducted by Achievers in 2020 found that 26% of employees who feel inadequately recognized and undervalued are twice as likely to quit their jobs within a year. Furthermore, 46% of new hires fail and are let go within eighteen months of being hired. Of those let go, 11% were due to lack of skills, while the remaining 89% were for behavioral reasons such as lack of motivation and/or lack of coachability.[^12] 

Despite these momentous benefits, when left unrecognized and untrained, managers will continue to forgo these opportunities. Employees view the process not as a legal requirement but as another required activity that must be completed. They will get it done but just to the extent of it being completed. To realize these benefits, both managers and employees need to be actively engaged and trained in the performance management process, and the first step would be to understand the expected performance standards, calibration standards, and the importance of goal setting. Through increased understanding, managers can provide clarity for any questions employees may have but also make the process more engaging, transparent, and fair. Employees, in turn, would become more involved, engaged, and proactive regarding this process, resulting in the desired benefits.

## **Comparison** {#comparison}

### **Microsoft**  {#microsoft}

As a recommendation, Goodwill's system for rewarding employees focuses on promotions as the primary pathway for salary increases. This somehow means that regardless of an individual’s performance within their role, raises are standardized across similar positions. High-performing employees receive the same salary adjustments as their peers, which might not reflect their efforts at work. Without tying rewards directly to performance, this structure is somewhat disengaging top talent who may feel their exceptional work is not adequately recognized., which often creates a disconnect for employees who consistently perform well but remain in the same role. High performers can feel undervalued when their efforts are acknowledged only through words rather than tangible benefits. This gap in the reward system can unintentionally lower morale, leading to disengagement or even turnover.

Microsoft, however, uses a merit based reward system that ensures employees are recognized and compensated for their performance, regardless of their role. Whether through bonuses, stock options, or raises, employees feel motivated to excel, knowing their contribution will be rewarded fairly. This always creates a work environment where everyone’s efforts are acknowledged and it matters, regardless of their position in the organizational hierarchy.

For Goodwill, adopting a merit based system could be transformative. Imagine employees who feel empowered because their hard work directly translates into financial rewards or career growth opportunities. This would not just improve productivity but it will align seamlessly with Goodwill’s mission of fostering dignity and individual sufficiency. Recognition doesn’t always have to mean a promotion as it can be a bonus, a raise, or even access to leadership programs. This shift could show employees that their value is acknowledged every step of the way, not just when they change roles.

Also, another area where Goodwill can be better is in preparing its employees and managers to fully utilize the PMP. At present, managers refer to the performance review process as a checkbox exercise like something to be completed to meet regulatory standards. Employees, in turn, perceive these reviews as an annual formality rather than a meaningful opportunity for growth. This lack of engagement stems from insufficient training on how to leverage PMP tools and processes effectively.

Microsoft also has other areas of training program initiation by offering robust training programs that help both managers and employees with the skills to strengthen their performance management system. Managers learn how to give constructive feedback or set realistic and inspiring goals, or align individual contributions with the company's further objectives. Employees also are trained to understand how to advocate for themselves during reviews, track their progress, and turn feedback into actionable steps.

For Goodwill, implementing a similar training framework could help to revolutionize its PMP. Where managers can approach performance reviews not as a task to complete but as an opportunity to help and uplift their teammates. Make employees understand how they can feel confident entering a review because they understand the process and their own potential. This is not just about teaching people to use tools, it is about building a culture where performance reviews become a dialogue like one that inspires, motivates, and drives meaningful change.

By creating a merit based reward system and introducing comprehensive PMP training for both managers and employees, Goodwill can unlock the full potential of its workforce. These changes would increase a sense of fairness and clarity, helping employees feel truly valued and supported. Taking inspiration from Microsoft’s employee-first strategies, Goodwill has the opportunity to transform its PMP into not just a system, but a cornerstone of its mission to uplift and empower shortly.

### **Uber / Netflix** {#uber-/-netflix}

One recommendation we came up with is incorporating employee involvement when constructing development and performance goals. Currently, Goodwill does not involve employees in the construction of development goals, they are instead crafted by the employee's manager or someone even higher. The closest item Goodwill has to be involved is a development questionnaire that has some questions that are potentially close to garnering employee feedback that could be used for a personal development goal. That said, the development questionnaire is only available to admin employees and above \- so baseline employees aren’t currently exposed to it. According to Bonfyre, soliciting employee input and an outlet to speak their minds increases their involvement and ownership providing a stronger commitment to their work.[^17] This demonstrates the value of eliciting employee input on many facets, including development and performance goals. Organizations are constantly striving for increased productivity, and this is one of the ways you can intrinsically motivate employees. Another potential strategy is Uber's T3 B3 approach. Uber adopted an approach they use as “top three bottom three,” where it asks employees to list their top three strengths and bottom 3 areas of improvement.[^18] The next part of this plan is fascinating, while historically Employees have been offered a bit more privacy when given performance goals \- Uber tries a different approach. They take your strengths and weaknesses to derive goals to work on and put them in a system that can be accessed by everyone, from employees to top executives. This is a game-changing level of transparency, and Uber says that this newer collaborative approach focuses on development rather than past behavior. This may be a good way to implement employee involvement in constructing development and performance goals, though this may vary depending on the organization. The overall idea though is the same, involving employees in the construction and creation of development and performance goals is a win-win for the employee and the organization as a whole as it increases productivity. 

  Another recommendation we have is implementing consistent frequent 360 feedback. It has been proven that employees that receive frequent feedback are more engaged leading to higher levels of productivity. Denise Mclain and Bailey Nelson from Gallup reference that data shows that 80% of employees who have received meaningful feedback in the past week are fully engaged. They mention a keyword being meaningful feedback, as well as frequent[^19]. This shows the imperativeness of needing to provide meaningful feedback, but also consistently and not just once a year. They recommend using a technique called Fast Feedback to ensure it’s more meaningful and leads to quicker and shorter feedback more frequently. They finally go on to mention the additional benefits that were discovered by using Fast Feedback, including making it more straightforward for managers and contributing towards a larger goal of creating a culture of feedback. Even organizations like Netflix, Google, Nissan, and Barclays utilize 360 feedback as they have noted the benefits[^20]. Even though both Netflix and Uber do the 360 feedback process formally, Netflix only does it annually as pointed out by Hannah Aster who references Reed Hastings (Cofounder and Chairman of Netflix) book “No Rules Rules,”[^21] while Uber attempts to do it more frequently. Goodwill doesn’t utilize any form of 360 feedback, instead relying on managers' sole feedback. This is an excellent area of opportunity where results only get better the longer you implement 360 feedback. Due to Uber's ultra-transparent performance management design with each employee's goals, anyone in the company can see any of your goals at any point in a team \- invites the opportunity for consistent frequent 360 feedback from everyone and anyone all the time. It also gives everyone a chance to focus on what they need to do today, to not do what they did incorrectly yesterday. It’s a very unique and interesting approach that also fosters a culture of collaboration and openness. People who are easily offended may not prefer this type of 360 feedback at first \- though if they’re able to adapt the long-term benefits are substantial in terms of increasing employee engagement and productivity.  

### **Deloitte** {#deloitte}

	An additional recommendation we would like to put forth is to calibrate the rating of the performance management process. In a study conducted by Michael Mount, Steven Scullen, and Maynard Goff which was published in the Journal of Applied Psychology in 2000, 4492 managers were rated on certain performance metrics by two bosses, two peers, and two subordinates. Through this, they found that 62% of the variance in ratings was attributed to the individual raters’ unique perspectives, while actual performance accounted for only 21% of the variance. This resulted in the conclusion that, although the act of rating someone implies the rating is based on the ratee, in actuality, it is more a reflection of the rater’s unique rating tendencies than the ratee’s performance. Knowing this statistic, Deloitte got rid of its previous method, which asked team leaders what they thought of each team member and changed to what they would do instead. People tend to have difficulty rating other people’s skills consistently but do not share that same issue when it comes to rating how they feel and their intentions moving forward. To capitalize on this, Deloitte developed these four gauging questions to generate accurate and rich data. One, “Given what I know of this person’s performance, and if it were my money, I would award this person the highest possible compensation increase and bonus.” This measures overall performance in addition to the unique value they bring to the organization using a five-point scale. Two, “Given what I know of this person’s performance, I would always want him or her on my team.” This measures their ability to work in collaboration also on a five-point scale. Three, “This person is at risk for low performance.” This identifies potential problems that may harm the customer or team on a yes-or-no basis. Lastly, four, “This person is ready for promotion today.” This measures their potential on a yes-or-no basis.[^22] Currently, at Goodwill, there is no calibration of ratings involved in the performance management process, and there should be to avoid inconsistent results. Is it enough to implement what Deloitte just moved away from due to the distortion of results even with calibration, or should we aspire for better? We believe it would be more effective to take one giant leap rather than two individual steps, as it would be more cost- and time-effective. As the performance-gauging questions developed by Deloitte are generic and insightful, we see no issue in taking them as is. After deploying them in a test run with a small batch of employees, we can customize them if needed. With this, like Deloitte, Goodwill will have accurate and rich data on each employee in the performance management process.

	Our last recommendation is to reiterate the importance of the performance management process across all levels of the company. However, in a public survey that Deloitte conducted, 58% of executives questioned believed that their company’s current performance management approach drives neither employee engagement nor high performance. Therefore, it was important to review and adjust one's performance management process before issuing such a critical declaration to ensure its effectiveness. To that end, Deloitte revamped its performance management process from the standard annual review with 360-degree feedback to recognize, see, and fuel performance. Through this, Deloitte was able to cut costs, recognize vital metrics, accurately see performance data, and fuel the desired change. These changes were implemented throughout the company and taken seriously at all levels as they factored in and considered all parties involved. For employees, there were more regular evaluations and frequent check-ins, which helped keep them motivated and aligned. As for managers and executives, they had less closed-door work, and more accurate and rich data to utilize.[^23] In Goodwill’s case, managers and above view the performance management process as a legal requirement set by CARF (Commission on Accreditation of Rehabilitation Facilities). Employees, on the other hand, see the performance management process as a work requirement and nothing else. By reiterating the importance of the performance management process to everyone, we are saying that this is more than a legal requirement; rather, it is a means to propel Goodwill forward and strengthen the company. Should we effectively convey this message, we can start to see the benefits of our newly revised performance management process noted in the other recommendations.

## **Challenges**  {#challenges}

	Change is never easy for a company, let alone a performance management process that evaluates an employee’s performance. As a group, we came up with 3 recommendations on how to improve Goodwill’s PMP. We will discuss the challenges that may come up during the implementation process. Such challenges include: resistant to change, lack of leadership, inadequate communication, insufficient resources, and disruption to existing routines.[^24] The challenges of recommending change to the Goodwill’s PMP need to be addressed before we can start making changes.

	The first recommendation is to provide constant formal/informal feedback at least every quarter to help employees recalibrate their goals and give them flexibility to improve their skills. To reiterate this, employees enjoy knowing how they are doing and appreciate the real time feedback. We recommended having informal feedback (quick check-ins, a look at the employee’s metrics, etc.) every quarter to gauge how each individual employee is doing. This allows time for employees to make any corrective measures sooner than later. For formal feedback (merit increases, setting development and performance goals, etc.), these can be accomplished bi-annulay to keep workers motivated and engaged. On paper, these sound great, but we are going to dive into how they can be challenging to implement. Having to set up meetings to provide constant feedback can be time-consuming and bothersome for both employees and managers. This can take away time from staff focusing on crucial business operations, hindering Goodwill’s revenue. Organizations often face limitations in terms of budget, staffing, and technology, Employees and managers may experience time constraints due to heavy workloads and competing priorities.[^25] Goodwill can reiterate to both employees and managers the importance of using Paycom to track real time feedback and communication within the workers. First we need to provide training on how to adequately use the software to increase user confidence. This will help automate administrative tasks and streamline the PMP.

	The second recommendation we provided is incorporating employee involvement when constructing development/performance goals and initiating frequent consistent formal 360 feedback. This integration means employees are meeting current expectations and advancing their skills. Currently, Goodwill only provides development goals, which is great for the long term, but we want to also implement performance goals for the short term to keep employees engaged in their role. The challenge we foresee implementing this is employees understanding the difference between a performance goal and a development goal. At a glance, it is hard to decipher what each goal entails, but both compliment each other very well if done correctly. If you only have a development goal but not a performance goal, you will not be able to focus on the end result. The key difference between the two is that a development goal focuses on learning while performance goals are job-oriented.[^26] Goodwill leadership will have to differentiate both, educate the employees, and allow them to come up with a performance goal at each informal feedback check in, and a development goal at each formal feedback session. This will allow for a clear vision of an employee's overall set goals. 360 feedback is a holistic approach to support workers to develop themselves appropriately, so they can achieve their performance targets. This will create confidence in the system and both employees and managers will have a clear understanding of what employee skills are needed to create positive business results.

	The last recommendation we provided is thoroughly gauging every employee’s performance, regardless of their role, and providing a fair merit increase. For those employees who do not meet Goodwill’s performance expectations, provide constructive feedback to help them develop their areas of improvement. So what is a merit increase? A Merit increase is a boost in pay as a result of an excellent performance or a promotion.[^27] A pay raise is an increase of the employee’s salary, but necessarily due to performance; it can be a regular annual increase or an inflation increase. There are a couple of challenges that we see coming from this. First, Goodwill’s HR department needs to differentiate the benefits of a merit increase and a regular pay raise and educate the employees. Currently, Goodwill provides the same rate of pay raises to employees, regardless of their performance. Goodwill leadership needs to carefully evaluate employee performance to determine if a merit increase or a pay raise is the right call. Secondly, providing merit increases can impact Goodwill's finance if not gauged correctly. Merit increases can be rewarded subjectively and reinforce a perception of favoritism, angering workers.[^28] Thirdly, there was a study done by Mercer’s 2024 Global Talent Trends that the merit process can be inefficient. Each year, HR spends about 1 hour during the merit review process and if you have at least 5,000 employees, that can accumulate to 5,000 of lost hours due to meetings that only average a 4% increase in salary. To combat this, HR leadership needs to carefully evaluate and gauge employee performance. Goodwill needs to make sure that merit increases are in the company’s budget and that it is worth the time and effort. Merit increases increase employee motivation, leading to higher performance, eventually leading to more company revenue.

	In Summary, recommendations may seem great on paper, but do come with challenges. We need to carefully analyze each recommendation and determine what is the best way to tackle these challenges. We have outlined some of the challenges that Goodwill can face if these recommendations are implemented. As long as we do our due diligence and take into account everything that can go wrong and find a plan to mitigate the problems, these implementations can effectively help Goodwill’s overall PMP.

# **Conclusion**  {#conclusion}

	Having a developed and well-executed performance management process is vital in any organization. When developed but poorly executed, we get lackluster results due to low overall involvement. In contrast, a well-executed but underdeveloped process will yield subpar results from poor planning. Goodwill presently has both an underdeveloped and poorly executed performance management process. However, by utilizing this report, we aspire to turn that around. This report highlights what makes a good performance management process, Goodwill’s current situation, and key recommendations that should be implemented. To further support these recommendations, comparisons were drawn from three successful companies, along with the creation of SMART goals to ensure smooth implementation. Additionally, a business case and challenges sections were generated to spotlight key wins and acknowledge future challenges. Through this report, we hope to provide insight into the current circumstances and a logical path forward. To conclude, here is a quote from Tiger Woods: “No matter how good you get, you can always get better, and that's the exciting part.”
